  "description": "Congruence is a way of saying that two integers leave the same remainder when divided by a given number. The numbers 17 and 5 are congruent modulo 12 because both leave a remainder of 5 when divided by 12 — or equivalently, because their difference 17−5=1217 - 5 = 12 is divisible by 12. Clock arithmetic is the most familiar example: 3 o\u0026rsquo;clock and 15 o\u0026rsquo;clock are the \u0026ldquo;same\u0026rdquo; time on a 12-hour clock, because 15≡3(mod12)15 \\equiv 3 \\pmod{12}.\n",
  "name": "Congruence",
